1
00:00:11,560 --> 00:00:13,100
A single drop of blood.

2
00:00:13,760 --> 00:00:16,220
A company worth nine billion dollars.

3
00:00:16,220 --> 00:00:18,560
A young founder on the cover of every

4
00:00:18,560 --> 00:00:21,120
magazine, hailed as the next Steve Jobs.

5
00:00:21,120 --> 00:00:22,440
And underneath all of it,

6
00:00:22,440 --> 00:00:25,060
a machine that did not actually do what

7
00:00:25,060 --> 00:00:27,800
the world was told it could do.

8
00:00:28,940 --> 00:00:32,280
The story of Theranos is the most famous

9
00:00:32,280 --> 00:00:34,340
fraud of the startup era — and it

10
00:00:34,340 --> 00:00:37,660
ends with a question that hangs over every

11
00:00:37,660 --> 00:00:39,000
bold promise ever made to investors:

12
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:39,725
when does selling a dream become a crime?

13
00:00:47,340 --> 00:00:49,900
For this whole series, we have watched the

14
00:00:49,900 --> 00:00:51,980
power of the state pressing against one person

15
00:00:53,650 --> 00:00:54,540
— searching you, tracking you,

16
00:00:54,900 --> 00:00:56,920
taking from you, following you home.

17
00:00:57,560 --> 00:00:59,500
This final story turns the camera completely

18
00:00:59,500 --> 00:00:59,920
around.

19
00:01:00,560 --> 00:01:02,700
Here, it is one person whose words reach

20
00:01:02,700 --> 00:01:03,300
everyone:

21
00:01:03,900 --> 00:01:05,880
the investors who put in hundreds of millions,

22
00:01:05,880 --> 00:01:08,240
and the patients who trusted their blood to

23
00:01:08,240 --> 00:01:08,740
a machine.

24
00:01:09,560 --> 00:01:11,000
Over the next twelve minutes:

25
00:01:11,360 --> 00:01:13,640
how Theranos rose, how it fell,

26
00:01:14,080 --> 00:01:16,320
and what a jury decided actually crossed the

27
00:01:16,320 --> 00:01:19,720
line from ambition into fraud — because that

28
00:01:19,720 --> 00:01:22,520
line, it turns out, is narrower and stranger

29
00:01:22,520 --> 00:01:23,600
than you might think.

30
00:01:35,330 --> 00:01:38,420
It begins in 2003, with a nineteen-year-old who

31
00:01:38,420 --> 00:01:40,300
drops out of Stanford to start a company.

32
00:01:40,980 --> 00:01:42,200
Her name is Elizabeth Holmes,

33
00:01:42,600 --> 00:01:44,400
and her idea is genuinely seductive.

34
00:01:44,400 --> 00:01:46,660
Today, a blood test means a needle,

35
00:01:47,220 --> 00:01:49,240
a vial, a lab, a wait.

36
00:01:50,140 --> 00:01:51,860
Holmes promised to erase all of that.

37
00:01:52,400 --> 00:01:55,480
Her company, Theranos, said its device — called

38
00:01:55,480 --> 00:01:57,940
the Edison — could run hundreds of tests

39
00:01:57,940 --> 00:02:00,620
from a single, painless drop of blood from

40
00:02:00,620 --> 00:02:02,660
your finger, quickly and cheaply,

41
00:02:02,960 --> 00:02:05,200
maybe one day in every drugstore and home.

42
00:02:05,760 --> 00:02:07,760
If it were real, it would change medicine.

43
00:02:08,480 --> 00:02:09,960
That "if" is the whole story.

44
00:02:10,320 --> 00:02:12,120
And the world wanted it to be real.

45
00:02:12,920 --> 00:02:13,860
Money poured in.

46
00:02:14,680 --> 00:02:16,560
At its peak, around 2014,

47
00:02:16,880 --> 00:02:19,000
Theranos was valued at roughly nine billion

48
00:02:19,820 --> 00:02:22,580
dollars, briefly making Holmes a paper billionaire

49
00:02:22,580 --> 00:02:24,620
and one of the most celebrated founders in

50
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:25,560
America.

51
00:02:25,560 --> 00:02:28,580
Its board filled with famous names — former

52
00:02:28,580 --> 00:02:30,380
statesmen and military leaders.

53
00:02:30,380 --> 00:02:32,760
It struck a deal with the pharmacy chain

54
00:02:32,760 --> 00:02:34,799
Walgreens to put its testing in some stores.

55
00:02:42,400 --> 00:02:44,560
And the prestige fed on itself.

56
00:02:45,320 --> 00:02:47,240
A board of household names made the company

57
00:02:47,240 --> 00:02:50,660
look unimpeachable; a soaring valuation made

58
00:02:50,660 --> 00:02:52,460
skeptics look foolish for doubting.

59
00:02:53,080 --> 00:02:55,460
Each famous believer became a reason for the

60
00:02:55,460 --> 00:02:57,240
next person not to look too closely.

61
00:02:57,900 --> 00:02:59,060
That is how a story,

62
00:02:59,060 --> 00:03:01,200
more than a product, can carry a company

63
00:03:01,200 --> 00:03:01,720
for years.

64
00:03:02,380 --> 00:03:03,880
Notice what made this so powerful.

65
00:03:04,560 --> 00:03:06,580
It was not just a product; it was

66
00:03:06,580 --> 00:03:09,100
a story — a brilliant young woman,

67
00:03:09,620 --> 00:03:12,800
a revolutionary machine, a future where a drop

68
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:14,340
of blood could save your life.

69
00:03:15,460 --> 00:03:17,800
Investors, reporters, and partners all wanted to

70
00:03:17,800 --> 00:03:18,480
be part of it.

71
00:03:19,020 --> 00:03:21,120
And a beautiful enough story can make very

72
00:03:21,120 --> 00:03:23,620
smart people stop asking the most basic question:

73
00:03:24,520 --> 00:03:26,000
does the thing actually work?

74
00:03:37,620 --> 00:03:40,480
In 2015, someone finally asked it in print.

75
00:03:41,200 --> 00:03:42,320
A Wall Street Journal reporter,

76
00:03:42,580 --> 00:03:45,080
John Carreyrou, published an investigation built

77
00:03:45,080 --> 00:03:47,060
on internal documents and whistleblowers.

78
00:03:47,740 --> 00:03:49,180
What it reported was devastating.

79
00:03:49,860 --> 00:03:51,920
The Edison did not work as advertised.

80
00:03:52,700 --> 00:03:54,720
Behind the scenes, the investigation said,

81
00:03:55,480 --> 00:03:57,280
Theranos was running many of its blood tests

82
00:03:57,480 --> 00:03:59,040
not on its own revolutionary device,

83
00:03:59,720 --> 00:04:02,200
but on ordinary commercial machines made by other

84
00:04:02,200 --> 00:04:04,680
companies — the very kind of equipment it

85
00:04:04,680 --> 00:04:05,700
claimed to have replaced.

86
00:04:06,140 --> 00:04:08,800
And the finger-prick results it did produce had

87
00:04:08,800 --> 00:04:10,300
serious accuracy problems.

88
00:04:10,860 --> 00:04:12,940
For a tech demo, unreliable results are an

89
00:04:12,940 --> 00:04:13,340
embarrassment.

90
00:04:14,080 --> 00:04:16,160
For a medical test, they are something else

91
00:04:16,160 --> 00:04:18,920
entirely — because real people were making real

92
00:04:18,920 --> 00:04:20,680
health decisions based on the numbers.

93
00:04:21,200 --> 00:04:22,520
From there, the fall was fast.

94
00:04:23,240 --> 00:04:24,100
Regulators moved in.

95
00:04:24,660 --> 00:04:26,120
The Walgreens partnership ended.

96
00:04:26,660 --> 00:04:29,480
In 2018, the Securities and Exchange Commission

97
00:04:29,480 --> 00:04:32,540
charged Holmes with fraud, and she settled those

98
00:04:32,540 --> 00:04:35,260
civil charges without admitting or denying

99
00:04:35,260 --> 00:04:38,300
wrongdoing — paying a penalty and accepting a

100
00:04:38,300 --> 00:04:39,800
ban from leading a public company.

101
00:04:40,440 --> 00:04:42,420
That same year, Theranos dissolved.

102
00:04:42,920 --> 00:04:45,280
The nine-billion-dollar company was worth nothing.

103
00:04:52,160 --> 00:04:54,680
But a collapsed company and a civil settlement

104
00:04:54,680 --> 00:04:56,160
are not the same as a crime.

105
00:04:56,760 --> 00:05:00,279
The harder question — the criminal one —

106
00:05:00,280 --> 00:05:00,340
was still coming.

107
00:05:00,860 --> 00:05:03,940
Did Elizabeth Holmes simply fail at something hard

108
00:05:03,940 --> 00:05:05,060
while believing in it?

109
00:05:05,380 --> 00:05:07,800
Or did she knowingly deceive the people who

110
00:05:07,800 --> 00:05:08,420
trusted her?

111
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:10,540
Those are not the same thing,

112
00:05:10,860 --> 00:05:12,800
and the difference between them is the difference

113
00:05:12,800 --> 00:05:14,980
between a sad story and a prison sentence.

114
00:05:26,480 --> 00:05:28,580
That question went to a federal court,

115
00:05:28,580 --> 00:05:30,460
in the case United States v.

116
00:05:30,460 --> 00:05:30,860
Holmes.

117
00:05:31,840 --> 00:05:33,040
And to understand the verdict,

118
00:05:33,400 --> 00:05:35,840
you have to understand what fraud actually is,

119
00:05:35,840 --> 00:05:36,300
legally.

120
00:05:37,300 --> 00:05:38,260
Fraud is not failure.

121
00:05:38,960 --> 00:05:40,800
It is not even lying in some loose,

122
00:05:40,800 --> 00:05:41,600
everyday sense.

123
00:05:42,600 --> 00:05:45,860
Criminal fraud requires intent to deceive — proof

124
00:05:45,860 --> 00:05:48,500
that a person knowingly made false statements to

125
00:05:48,500 --> 00:05:50,900
get something of value from someone who relied

126
00:05:50,900 --> 00:05:51,340
on them.

127
00:05:51,840 --> 00:05:54,260
A founder who genuinely believes in a product

128
00:05:54,260 --> 00:05:56,380
that does not pan out has not committed

129
00:05:56,380 --> 00:05:56,860
a crime.

130
00:05:57,450 --> 00:05:59,720
A founder who knows the truth and hides

131
00:05:59,720 --> 00:06:01,380
it to keep the money flowing has.

132
00:06:02,180 --> 00:06:04,120
The entire trial was a fight over which

133
00:06:04,120 --> 00:06:05,920
of those describes Elizabeth Holmes.

134
00:06:06,480 --> 00:06:08,560
At trial, the two sides told that exact

135
00:06:08,560 --> 00:06:09,520
split-screen story.

136
00:06:10,700 --> 00:06:12,600
Prosecutors argued that Holmes knew about the

137
00:06:12,600 --> 00:06:14,260
device's failures and hid them,

138
00:06:14,660 --> 00:06:16,840
pointing to internal results and warnings she had

139
00:06:16,840 --> 00:06:17,160
received.

140
00:06:17,820 --> 00:06:19,720
Her defense argued that she was a true

141
00:06:19,720 --> 00:06:22,120
believer who genuinely thought the technology

142
00:06:22,120 --> 00:06:24,560
would work, and that being wrong is not

143
00:06:24,560 --> 00:06:25,280
the same as lying.

144
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:27,600
The jury's job was to decide,

145
00:06:27,880 --> 00:06:30,660
count by count, which story the evidence supported

146
00:06:30,660 --> 00:06:32,060
beyond a reasonable doubt.

147
00:06:32,600 --> 00:06:35,160
On January 3rd, 2022, the jury delivered a

148
00:06:35,160 --> 00:06:37,020
verdict — and it was not a simple

149
00:06:37,020 --> 00:06:37,300
one.

150
00:06:37,900 --> 00:06:40,040
It convicted Holmes on four counts of fraud

151
00:06:40,040 --> 00:06:40,860
against investors:

152
00:06:41,460 --> 00:06:44,280
one count of conspiracy, and three counts of

153
00:06:44,280 --> 00:06:47,720
wire fraud, for deceiving specific investors who

154
00:06:47,720 --> 00:06:48,740
had put in large sums.

155
00:06:49,480 --> 00:06:51,300
On those counts, the jury found that she

156
00:06:51,300 --> 00:06:53,580
had crossed the line — that she knowingly

157
00:06:53,580 --> 00:06:55,420
deceived the people funding the company.

158
00:07:15,340 --> 00:07:17,420
But on the counts that accused her of

159
00:07:17,420 --> 00:07:20,160
defrauding patients, the jury found her not

160
00:07:20,160 --> 00:07:20,620
guilty.

161
00:07:21,060 --> 00:07:22,840
And on three more investor counts,

162
00:07:23,120 --> 00:07:24,600
the jurors could not agree at all,

163
00:07:25,160 --> 00:07:27,180
so the judge declared a mistrial on those.

164
00:07:27,940 --> 00:07:30,240
Convicted on some, acquitted on others,

165
00:07:30,860 --> 00:07:31,760
deadlocked on the rest.

166
00:07:32,360 --> 00:07:34,220
It is tempting to read the patient acquittals

167
00:07:34,220 --> 00:07:36,740
as a verdict that the technology was fine,

168
00:07:36,740 --> 00:07:38,380
or that no one was hurt.

169
00:07:39,160 --> 00:07:39,900
It is not.

170
00:07:40,780 --> 00:07:43,260
An acquittal means only that the prosecution did

171
00:07:43,260 --> 00:07:45,920
not prove those particular charges beyond a

172
00:07:45,920 --> 00:07:48,520
reasonable doubt — the highest bar in law

173
00:07:50,624 --> 00:07:51,820
— not that the underlying conduct was harmless.

174
00:07:52,680 --> 00:07:55,020
One juror later suggested the patient link was

175
00:07:55,020 --> 00:07:57,580
simply harder to pin directly on Holmes.

176
00:07:58,260 --> 00:08:00,180
And the contrast makes the point sharply:

177
00:08:01,120 --> 00:08:04,580
Theranos's former president, Ramesh Balwani — her

178
00:08:04,580 --> 00:08:07,400
business and former romantic partner — was tried

179
00:08:07,400 --> 00:08:09,620
separately, and he was convicted on all twelve

180
00:08:09,620 --> 00:08:11,880
counts, including the patient counts,

181
00:08:12,240 --> 00:08:14,160
and sentenced to nearly thirteen years.

182
00:08:14,680 --> 00:08:15,440
As for Holmes:

183
00:08:15,660 --> 00:08:18,140
in November 2022, she was sentenced to about

184
00:08:18,140 --> 00:08:20,020
eleven years and three months in federal prison.

185
00:08:20,840 --> 00:08:22,740
The young woman once compared to Steve Jobs

186
00:08:22,740 --> 00:08:25,180
was now a convicted fraudster — but,

187
00:08:25,180 --> 00:08:27,680
precisely, a fraudster of investors,

188
00:08:27,680 --> 00:08:30,600
on four specific counts proven to a jury.

189
00:08:42,160 --> 00:08:44,340
So where, exactly, is the line that Holmes

190
00:08:44,340 --> 00:08:44,660
crossed?

191
00:08:45,360 --> 00:08:47,220
Because here is the uncomfortable truth:

192
00:08:47,820 --> 00:08:49,740
a lot of what Theranos did looks like

193
00:08:49,740 --> 00:08:51,020
ordinary startup behavior.

194
00:08:52,300 --> 00:08:54,300
Founders pitch a future that does not exist

195
00:08:54,300 --> 00:08:54,620
yet.

196
00:08:55,280 --> 00:08:57,660
They project confidence they do not fully feel.

197
00:08:58,540 --> 00:09:00,040
"Fake it till you make it" is practically

198
00:09:00,040 --> 00:09:02,620
a Silicon Valley slogan, and most of the

199
00:09:02,620 --> 00:09:03,800
time the law leaves it alone.

200
00:09:04,380 --> 00:09:05,800
The line is intent and reliance.

201
00:09:06,840 --> 00:09:08,380
Selling an ambitious vision is legal.

202
00:09:09,160 --> 00:09:11,860
Knowingly telling people something false — that a

203
00:09:11,860 --> 00:09:13,520
machine works when you know it does not

204
00:09:14,000 --> 00:09:15,700
— to get them to hand over money

205
00:09:15,700 --> 00:09:17,040
they would not otherwise risk,

206
00:09:17,040 --> 00:09:17,860
is fraud.

207
00:09:18,820 --> 00:09:20,760
The jury concluded that, with investors,

208
00:09:20,760 --> 00:09:23,120
Holmes had done exactly that.

209
00:09:30,300 --> 00:09:32,420
And there is a reason the stakes felt

210
00:09:32,420 --> 00:09:35,140
higher here than in an ordinary bad investment.

211
00:09:35,860 --> 00:09:37,320
A failed app costs you money.

212
00:09:37,880 --> 00:09:39,760
A blood test that gives the wrong answer

213
00:09:39,760 --> 00:09:41,280
can cost you a diagnosis.

214
00:09:42,040 --> 00:09:44,280
That is why the patient dimension haunted the

215
00:09:44,280 --> 00:09:47,140
whole case, even where the specific counts did

216
00:09:47,140 --> 00:09:49,920
not stick to Holmes — and why Balwani's

217
00:09:49,920 --> 00:09:52,020
conviction on those counts matters to the full

218
00:09:52,020 --> 00:09:52,400
picture.

219
00:10:04,160 --> 00:10:05,840
Theranos is where this series ends,

220
00:10:05,840 --> 00:10:07,920
and it is a fitting place — because

221
00:10:07,920 --> 00:10:09,820
under every episode we have watched,

222
00:10:09,820 --> 00:10:11,140
there has been one question,

223
00:10:11,140 --> 00:10:12,640
wearing different costumes.

224
00:10:13,100 --> 00:10:14,620
The police searching your pockets,

225
00:10:15,040 --> 00:10:17,460
tracking your phone, taking your property,

226
00:10:17,980 --> 00:10:20,500
swabbing your cheek, following you to your door

227
00:10:21,223 --> 00:10:23,220
— and now a founder selling a miracle

228
00:10:23,220 --> 00:10:24,120
that was not real.

229
00:10:25,020 --> 00:10:27,060
Each time, the law's job was the same:

230
00:10:27,460 --> 00:10:28,520
to find the line.

231
00:10:29,100 --> 00:10:31,040
The line between a stop and an arrest.

232
00:10:31,760 --> 00:10:34,540
Between identifying you and investigating you.

233
00:10:34,740 --> 00:10:36,980
Between a bold promise and a deliberate lie.

234
00:10:44,040 --> 00:10:46,240
That is what all of these cases really

235
00:10:46,240 --> 00:10:49,300
are — not dramatic stories about famous people,

236
00:10:49,740 --> 00:10:51,900
but arguments about where a line falls,

237
00:10:51,900 --> 00:10:55,800
as technology, money, and power keep moving it.

238
00:10:56,360 --> 00:10:59,240
The Constitution does not draw those lines once

239
00:10:59,240 --> 00:10:59,820
and for all.

240
00:11:00,340 --> 00:11:01,700
It hands us the tools,

241
00:11:01,700 --> 00:11:03,960
and every generation has to pick them up

242
00:11:03,960 --> 00:11:05,040
and draw them again.

243
00:11:10,080 --> 00:11:11,780
Thank you for watching this series.

244
00:11:12,310 --> 00:11:13,740
If you want to keep seeing how a

245
00:11:13,740 --> 00:11:15,760
single case can redraw the rules we all

246
00:11:15,760 --> 00:11:18,540
live by, this channel will keep finding them

247
00:11:18,762 --> 00:11:19,880
— one line at a time.
